You are trying to mock the constructor of an external class. Instead, change your code to use a factory instead which calls the constructor. You can then easily stub the factory method to throw the exception.

So going from a direct constructor call:

```
class YourClass {
  method() {
    final SomeClass obj = new SomeClass();
    // ...
  }
}
```

refactor the code to create the instance via a factory. Java 8+ makes this an easy task by leveraging method refs and lambdas:

```
class YourClass {
  @VisibleForTesting
  Supplier&lt;SomeClass&gt; makeSomeClass = SomeClass::new;
  method() {
    final SomeClass obj = makeSomeClass.get();
    // ...
  }
}

class YourClassTest {
  @Test
  void test() {
    final YourClass yourObj = new YourClass();
    yourObj.makeSomeClass = () -&gt; {
      throw new RuntimeException();
    };

    assertThatCode(() -&gt; yourObj.method())
        .isInstanceOf(RuntimeException.class);
  }
}
```

You don&#39;t even need Mockito :)

